WEBVTT

00:44.545 --> 00:50.050
The Warriors, the Knicks,
from Madison Square Garden in New York.

00:50.133 --> 00:53.011
Brian Anderson along with
the Hall of Famer Reggie Miller.

00:53.095 --> 00:55.472
An honor to be here tonight on this night

00:55.556 --> 00:58.308
when Stephen Curry
is on the doorstep of history.

00:58.392 --> 01:00.519
And an honor to be next to you
on this night…

01:00.602 --> 01:05.566
Knick hats, guys.
Knick hats. Hats, guys. Knick hats.

01:06.400 --> 01:08.569
History in the making right here.

01:09.069 --> 01:12.114
Steph Curry is going to break
the record for the most three-pointers.

01:12.823 --> 01:14.575
This is the night he's gonna do it.

01:24.751 --> 01:25.586
Okay.

01:28.297 --> 01:29.631
Tell me when y'all are ready.

01:34.553 --> 01:39.766
"Far below NBA standard in regard
to explosiveness and athleticism."

01:41.602 --> 01:47.107
"At 6'2", he's extremely small
for the NBA shooting guard position.

01:47.983 --> 01:50.986
Do not rely on him to run your team."

01:55.657 --> 01:58.702
"Can overshoot and rush into shots.

01:59.494 --> 02:02.915
Doesn't like when defenses
are too physical with him.

02:03.749 --> 02:09.713
Not a great finisher around the basket
due to his size and physical attributes.

02:10.756 --> 02:14.009
Needs to add some muscle
to his upper body,

02:14.718 --> 02:18.055
but appears as though
he'll always be skinny."

02:22.017 --> 02:26.396
That was the draft report
on Stephen Curry.

02:33.028 --> 02:35.030
Look at the fans as they rise up

02:35.113 --> 02:38.158
as Curry
is bringing the basketball up here.

02:39.785 --> 02:42.079
Everyone here is standing
to witness history.

02:54.341 --> 02:55.259
For the record!

02:56.677 --> 02:59.721
It's good! There it is!

02:59.805 --> 03:06.061
Stephen Curry!
The all-time three-point king of the NBA!

03:09.982 --> 03:11.984
Stephen Curry stands alone

03:12.067 --> 03:15.696
as the most dominant distance shooter
the game has ever seen.

03:15.779 --> 03:20.200
2,974 threes and counting.

03:46.310 --> 03:48.270
Pointer three-god for real, son.

03:52.274 --> 03:53.859
Silver fox.

03:54.985 --> 03:56.737
I had the green light tonight.

03:56.820 --> 03:58.780
-The license to shoot.
-You have the license.

04:01.116 --> 04:03.535
All right, get the fuck outta here, bro.

04:03.619 --> 04:06.955
Sorry for my language, Mama. I'm so sorry.

04:08.165 --> 04:09.333
…came over here, bro. Like…

04:09.416 --> 04:11.168
I had to come over here and say what's up.

04:11.251 --> 04:12.085
Love you, brother.

04:12.169 --> 04:17.173
Love you too, dawg. Yo.
I keep on telling you, dawg.

04:17.257 --> 04:19.259
Remember the time
you thought I was a little white kid?

04:20.636 --> 04:22.930
I think about that shit all the time, yo.

04:23.013 --> 04:26.183
I mean, who knew this shit ten years ago?
Now you that guy.

04:26.266 --> 04:28.393
-It's crazy.
-Nothing about it makes any sense.

04:28.477 --> 04:29.937
Embrace that shit.

04:30.020 --> 04:31.313
-All right?
-All right. Absolutely.

04:31.396 --> 04:32.981
-Good luck, brother.
-Appreciate it, man.

04:34.983 --> 04:37.069
-I love that dude, man.
-Dude.

04:37.152 --> 04:39.571
Most misunderstood dude
in the fricking league right there.

04:48.872 --> 04:51.500
I couldn't imagine
a better way to celebrate

04:51.583 --> 04:55.629
something that means so much to me,
to my family.

04:56.630 --> 04:59.675
I could not have ever imagined,
like, this would be a reality.

05:01.260 --> 05:04.972
And to know that everybody
in this room has had a part in my life,

05:05.055 --> 05:07.140
my journey, in some way, shape or form--

05:07.224 --> 05:09.434
Like, y'all know what this means to me.
This number right here?

05:09.518 --> 05:10.644
Yeah, baby!

05:13.772 --> 05:14.773
Yeah!

05:16.483 --> 05:19.570
It's a number, but it has
so much context, so much history,

05:19.653 --> 05:22.906
and we all get to own that together,
so thank y'all so much.

05:37.254 --> 05:40.382
I'm constantly trying to find the space

05:41.717 --> 05:45.596
just to be able to survey my life,
survey what's going on.

05:48.765 --> 05:52.436
To let my mind think about
"How did I get here?"

05:57.816 --> 05:59.860
My mind goes back to those places.

06:02.362 --> 06:03.780
And I think about everything.

06:28.597 --> 06:30.516
When I was nine years old,

06:30.599 --> 06:34.686
I played on the ten-and-under AAU team
the Charlotte Stars.

06:36.271 --> 06:37.439
I remember looking around like,

06:37.523 --> 06:39.858
"I'm not as tall as him,
not as strong as him."

06:41.527 --> 06:44.071
I was the undersized scrawny kid
that was just trying to figure out

06:44.154 --> 06:46.240
how to make it
at whatever level I was playing.

06:52.037 --> 06:55.582
That was when I first
really understood I'm different.

06:57.835 --> 07:02.005
And the temptation for me at that time
was to think about what I couldn't do.

07:03.882 --> 07:05.509
But I knew I could shoot.

07:05.592 --> 07:08.804
That was part
of what I brought to the team.

07:11.223 --> 07:14.268
[Sonya] Stephen! Good job, good job.

07:16.520 --> 07:17.688
Stephen!

07:21.024 --> 07:22.276
How old is he?

07:22.901 --> 07:26.154
[Sonya]
Fifteen. But he hasn't hit puberty yet.

07:26.655 --> 07:28.740
[Sonya] I asked the doctor,
I was starting to get worried.

07:31.827 --> 07:33.370
In my freshman year in high school,

07:33.912 --> 07:37.416
it was the first time I started
to think about, "What if I don't grow?"

07:39.501 --> 07:41.503
But also, like, "I know I can play."

07:46.842 --> 07:49.094
It never killed my love for the game.

07:50.429 --> 07:52.556
But it was a very difficult time,

07:53.724 --> 07:56.768
'cause I had to learn
how to embrace the challenge of it.

08:02.399 --> 08:06.737
His sophomore year, he said,
"I wanna play in college."

08:08.614 --> 08:10.866
He's, you know, probably, at that time,

08:11.491 --> 08:15.621
5'10", 5'11". Skinny.

08:15.704 --> 08:17.206
He's shooting from his waist.

08:17.956 --> 08:20.334
You know, younger co-- in high school,
you can get away with that,

08:20.417 --> 08:22.586
but I'm like, "Okay, if you wanna pl--
go to the next level,

08:23.712 --> 08:27.049
you gotta change your shot
from your waist. You gotta get up here."

08:32.011 --> 08:36.475
You gotta develop a totally different
set of muscles to make a change like that.

08:40.979 --> 08:44.900
Stephen was all in for the idea of it,

08:44.983 --> 08:50.155
until Dell took him out in the back
and he had to start shooting.

08:52.908 --> 08:56.954
It was a tough summer.
Me and Sonya, we both worked with him.

08:58.705 --> 09:03.085
For probably the first week,
he's just shooting right under the basket.

09:03.961 --> 09:08.465
Shot after shot, for hours every day.

09:10.425 --> 09:12.386
I was lost for a while.

09:13.470 --> 09:17.349
For three months, I literally
couldn't shoot outside of the paint.

09:19.601 --> 09:22.646
And he was just struggling.

09:23.272 --> 09:24.940
He was like, "I don't wanna do this.

09:25.023 --> 09:28.902
Why do I have to do this?
I can't keep going."

09:30.445 --> 09:32.990
And I was like,
"So, you have a choice, Son.

09:33.073 --> 09:34.575
You always have choices.

09:34.658 --> 09:38.954
If this is too frustrating for you
and you don't feel that it's valuable,

09:39.037 --> 09:42.916
stop now, go back to what you've--
how you've been shooting,

09:43.000 --> 09:44.585
and let's move on with this thing.

09:45.085 --> 09:49.923
But if you really are buying into
what your dad has prescribed for you,

09:51.258 --> 09:52.092
keep going."

10:09.985 --> 10:12.279
Nice. Release there.

10:14.239 --> 10:20.662
Three. Four. Four. Two.

10:23.415 --> 10:24.416
Here we go.

10:32.424 --> 10:33.967
Add a tennis ball to that.

10:41.517 --> 10:42.559
That's it.

10:53.737 --> 10:54.821
SLDL.

11:04.373 --> 11:07.417
Forty-five. Forty-five. Here we go.

11:09.211 --> 11:10.587
Watch, watch, watch. Coming here.

11:11.880 --> 11:12.881
I got it.

11:17.970 --> 11:19.096
Minus one.

11:23.183 --> 11:25.394
Even. Keep flowing. Just let it flow.

11:26.270 --> 11:27.896
-Keep up. Keep going.
-Lines.

11:29.147 --> 11:30.941
-Hustle.
-Come on.

11:31.567 --> 11:32.693
Beat, one, two.

11:34.444 --> 11:37.698
-Get in. Get in! Game.
-Come on! Hey!

11:38.448 --> 11:40.033
Perfection to finish.

11:40.117 --> 11:41.118
Yeah!

11:41.201 --> 11:43.620
Alternating range. Perfection to finish.

11:45.122 --> 11:48.375
Come on. Way to shoot it,
way to shoot it, way to shoot it.

11:48.458 --> 11:49.835
Good job, man. Good job, man.

12:10.731 --> 12:11.899
Hey, y'all. Welcome to Rightnowish.

12:11.982 --> 12:13.859
I'm your host, Pendarvis Harshaw.

12:13.942 --> 12:15.861
The Bay Bridge
still backed up to the overpasses,

12:15.944 --> 12:17.988
and there's also a report of a cra--

12:18.071 --> 12:20.407
95.7 The Game.

12:21.617 --> 12:23.577
In an absolute clunker in the Big Easy,

12:23.660 --> 12:28.123
the Warriors lose to the Pels 101-96.
They fall to 29-9.

12:28.707 --> 12:30.334
Should the Warriors be worried?

12:30.417 --> 12:33.629
Since their first 20 games,
they have been significantly worse.

12:33.712 --> 12:35.797
They're just not as dominant.

12:36.298 --> 12:38.467
I just keep thinking back
to the young version of the Warriors

12:38.550 --> 12:41.178
from a few years ago,
because they're not built the same way.

12:41.261 --> 12:42.721
It's just not the same team.

12:43.388 --> 12:46.350
And if Steph isn't gonna be MVP Steph,

12:46.433 --> 12:49.728
I don't think that the Warriors
are legitimate contenders.

13:11.917 --> 13:14.711
And starting at number 20 is a Junior.

13:14.795 --> 13:16.797
Steven Curry.

13:18.799 --> 13:21.176
That's Stephen Curry, you bum.

13:24.346 --> 13:25.639
What?

13:27.558 --> 13:28.892
Man, that was nuts.

13:30.978 --> 13:32.896
Man, that is crazy. That is…

13:38.443 --> 13:41.947
In my mind, I was thinking,
"That was interesting.

13:43.949 --> 13:45.492
He wasn't doing that last year.

13:46.076 --> 13:47.744
There's some improvement here.

13:49.246 --> 13:53.125
Look at his shot. Look at his pace.
Look at how he creates."

14:00.340 --> 14:04.928
Stephen Curry!

14:06.388 --> 14:11.185
There is just an art to what this kid
is doing out on the floor,

14:11.810 --> 14:16.064
and there is a drive
to be the absolute best.

14:26.283 --> 14:28.619
I started to play
pretty well in my junior year.

14:30.329 --> 14:32.206
And it created a little bit of a buzz.

14:36.335 --> 14:38.629
I wanted nothing more
than to go to Virginia Tech.

14:41.298 --> 14:43.383
My mom and my dad both went there.

14:45.969 --> 14:48.430
My dad's jersey's hanging in the rafters.

14:50.057 --> 14:53.852
There was a lot of conversation around
"were they gonna recruit me?"

14:57.898 --> 15:00.234
So, the Virginia Tech coach
came to the house.

15:02.277 --> 15:07.366
And he said, "You can definitely play.
No doubt. We see the skill.

15:10.118 --> 15:12.996
But we don't have a spot here.

15:14.623 --> 15:16.500
Well, he's too little.
He's gonna get pushed around.

15:16.583 --> 15:21.338
He's not big enough
to play major D1 basketball."

15:25.259 --> 15:29.805
I think that speaks to
how much I didn't pass the height test.

15:33.976 --> 15:38.146
But I really felt like
I could play with all those guys,

15:39.106 --> 15:41.942
if I can just
get an opportunity somewhere.

15:47.990 --> 15:49.449
Hey, let's go!

16:10.345 --> 16:14.725
Well, today it was clear
you played as if it was not robotic,

16:14.808 --> 16:17.519
as if I'm not
trying to get through practice.

16:17.603 --> 16:21.190
It was as-- It was a gift. It was a gift
to have this opportunity to play,

16:21.273 --> 16:22.649
and that's the way you played today.

16:22.733 --> 16:26.278
So obviously you played well,
obviously you played with confidence,

16:26.361 --> 16:27.529
and obviously we got better.

16:27.613 --> 16:32.534
So we accomplished a lot today,
all because of your attitude. Tremendous.

16:32.618 --> 16:34.036
Okay, now we gotta keep this going.

16:34.119 --> 16:36.163
-One, two, three, TCC.
-TCC!

17:04.233 --> 17:08.694
In 2005, several stories
in The Charlotte Observer popped up

17:08.779 --> 17:12.574
about someone named Stephen Curry
playing for Charlotte Christian.

17:13.951 --> 17:15.536
We started to pay attention.

17:16.036 --> 17:20.665
Not so much
as a high-profile focus of ours

17:20.749 --> 17:24.752
but someone
who we should just go and watch.

17:26.964 --> 17:29.424
Steph was mentioned as a player,

17:30.676 --> 17:31.844
but it wasn't like,

17:31.927 --> 17:34.972
"We have to go down to Charlotte Christian
and see Steph Curry play.

17:35.055 --> 17:38.141
You can't believe it when
you see him play." It was just a mention.

17:39.810 --> 17:43.814
I don't believe many schools
had walked in to watch Stephen play.

17:43.897 --> 17:45.357
Yeah!

17:46.400 --> 17:52.072
But we watched. We saw. We liked.

17:59.288 --> 18:03.125
It was interesting,
because he missed shots,

18:04.168 --> 18:07.754
he made turnovers, he made bad plays.

18:09.715 --> 18:10.883
But he never stopped playing.

18:12.301 --> 18:16.346
The next opportunity he had,
he would make a spectacular play.

18:18.724 --> 18:23.020
He showed a real emotional toughness,
which is so rare.

18:25.063 --> 18:28.025
So, we decided that
we were gonna recruit him.

18:34.823 --> 18:38.368
In the beginning,
I remember having very good conversations

18:38.452 --> 18:43.081
with Steph about Davidson, about his game.

18:44.208 --> 18:45.959
So we were feeling really, really good.

18:49.171 --> 18:52.799
And then all of a sudden,
I couldn't get Steph on the phone.

18:56.261 --> 18:58.013
And I had the sense that, "Oh, no.

18:59.014 --> 19:02.142
That means all these colleges
are now getting involved,

19:02.226 --> 19:04.228
and it's starting to blow up on us."

19:06.855 --> 19:08.273
So, I started to panic.

19:09.942 --> 19:11.985
I start reaching out
to his high school coach.

19:12.486 --> 19:15.239
I start reaching out to people around him.

19:16.240 --> 19:17.407
And still nothing.

19:21.995 --> 19:26.667
And I finally, about ten days later,
get Steph on the phone.

19:27.793 --> 19:31.171
And he goes, "Yeah, Coach,
my mother took my phone away from me.

19:32.130 --> 19:36.134
A friend of mine text me a curse word.

19:37.469 --> 19:40.764
I didn't send the text.
A friend sent a curse word to me,

19:40.848 --> 19:43.642
so my mother took my phone away
for two weeks."

19:47.020 --> 19:48.021
Let's go!

19:51.775 --> 19:55.821
At that point, when I realized
that other offers weren't coming,

19:56.697 --> 20:00.158
it became very clear that
I was on a different journey.

20:00.242 --> 20:02.494
Three-point basket is good.

20:02.578 --> 20:06.331
But Coach McKillop painted a vision
of what Davidson could mean for me,

20:06.415 --> 20:09.626
what him coaching me could mean for me
reaching my full potential.

20:12.212 --> 20:14.965
That year, we were losing seven seniors.

20:16.049 --> 20:20.304
And I think Stephen saw
an opportunity for himself

20:20.888 --> 20:23.182
and we told him about that opportunity.

20:23.891 --> 20:27.060
I think that excited him,
and that was even one more

20:28.896 --> 20:31.940
piece of the puzzle for him
as he made his decision.

20:37.738 --> 20:39.823
So, Matt Matheny and I
drove into Charlotte,

20:40.824 --> 20:45.913
sat down with everyone together
to answer every question

20:45.996 --> 20:48.373
that they might have about Davidson.

20:50.167 --> 20:54.588
We were two or three minutes
into the conversation,

20:54.671 --> 20:56.590
and Steph said, "Stop.

20:57.883 --> 20:58.967
Coach, just stop a second."

21:01.011 --> 21:03.013
And he says, "I've made my decision.

21:04.139 --> 21:05.516
I wanna be a Wildcat."

21:06.016 --> 21:08.477
And we were like,
"Oh, my gosh, that's fantastic!"

21:08.560 --> 21:10.604
We were dancing in the living room.

21:11.438 --> 21:13.023
There was a shot of adrenaline.

21:13.607 --> 21:14.608
There was…

21:15.859 --> 21:18.278
the sense that we just got a steal.

21:18.779 --> 21:20.948
No one knows how good this guy's gonna be.

21:21.448 --> 21:23.617
He is a perfect fit for what we do.

21:25.410 --> 21:29.540
So, before Coach left,
my mom thanked him for the opportunity.

21:30.374 --> 21:31.834
And the last thing she said was,

21:31.917 --> 21:33.961
"Don't worry, Coach,
we'll fatten him up for you."

21:34.795 --> 21:37.714
And Coach turned around
and looked at her and was like,

21:37.798 --> 21:41.009
"Don't worry about that.
We'll take him just the way he is."

21:41.510 --> 21:45.389
That gave me so much confidence
in terms of his appreciation for

21:46.682 --> 21:47.808
What I bring to the table.

21:48.392 --> 21:49.393
Like…

21:50.644 --> 21:53.480
I'm different,
but I have something to offer.

21:58.986 --> 21:59.987
I felt great.

22:01.196 --> 22:03.824
I really felt like
I had made the right decision.

22:05.993 --> 22:09.496
So, I went to watch a school football game
two or three days later,

22:10.664 --> 22:12.499
and I told, like, all my friends, like,

22:12.583 --> 22:15.169
"Yo, I know where
I'm going to school next year.

22:16.170 --> 22:17.337
I'm going to Davidson."

22:19.047 --> 22:21.675
And nobody knew where it was.
It was like--

22:22.509 --> 22:25.929
like, that hype in that moment
for me was so dope,

22:26.013 --> 22:28.932
and then nobody could really meet me
on that level emotionally,

22:29.016 --> 22:30.893
like, to celebrate it with me.

22:40.819 --> 22:42.070
Look at this one.

22:45.991 --> 22:51.622
I remember when Coach McKillop
came to recruit Stephen at the house,

22:52.122 --> 22:56.877
one of the things that he said
to Stephen was,

22:56.960 --> 22:58.879
"I can get you on stage.

22:58.962 --> 23:00.839
It's up to you what you'll do."

23:01.673 --> 23:03.342
What I liked so much is that

23:03.425 --> 23:05.928
it's not even necessarily about
proving other people wrong.

23:06.011 --> 23:07.804
-It's about proving…
-It's himself.

23:07.888 --> 23:09.806
-…himself right.
-Exactly. Yep.

23:09.890 --> 23:12.309
It was just, like, a different time.

23:12.392 --> 23:13.810
-Yeah.
-You know?

23:13.894 --> 23:16.396
He was so itty-bitty

23:16.897 --> 23:18.815
and everybody was picking on him,

23:18.899 --> 23:21.235
talking about he was too small to play.

23:21.318 --> 23:23.695
You remember when the man
was up in the stands,

23:23.779 --> 23:25.656
and he was calling them punks and stuff?

23:25.739 --> 23:28.158
I said, "Say one more thing,

23:28.242 --> 23:30.035
I'ma bust you in your mouth."

23:30.118 --> 23:31.995
I was gonna climb over that seat.

23:32.496 --> 23:34.665
-Not climb over the seat.
-I told him,

23:34.748 --> 23:36.250
"Don't talk about my grandson."

23:37.668 --> 23:39.920
-I remember.
-"Don't talk about my grandson."

23:45.425 --> 23:48.387
Remember I used to say
he looked like the Cabbage Patch doll?

23:53.267 --> 23:56.228
He was definitely an unplanned pregnancy.

23:56.895 --> 23:58.981
'Cause I wanted
to get through college first.

23:59.773 --> 24:01.984
And then I brought Stephen back with me,

24:02.067 --> 24:03.402
Seth back.

24:03.485 --> 24:08.740
Stephen was two and a half,
and he turned three when I graduated.

24:08.824 --> 24:10.492
How'd you have time for homework?

24:10.576 --> 24:12.160
-I know.
-You just did it.

24:12.244 --> 24:14.538
You just did it.
I really wanted to get my degree.

24:14.621 --> 24:17.374
-I get emotional thinking about it.
-Definitely.

24:17.457 --> 24:21.044
I was the first one in my family
to get my degree,

24:21.128 --> 24:25.090
and to me it was always like
something was unfinished.

24:29.761 --> 24:34.725
When Stephen decided to
declare for the NBA a year early,

24:35.475 --> 24:36.977
I wanted him to really understand

24:37.060 --> 24:39.271
how important it was
for him to get his degree.

24:40.230 --> 24:41.481
But then also,

24:41.565 --> 24:46.570
Stephen is the only player
who has not gotten their degree

24:46.653 --> 24:48.906
under the tutelage of Coach McKillop.

24:49.656 --> 24:53.410
So, it has been a thorn in his side
from me.

24:55.204 --> 24:57.956
And then he'll be like,
"I just won three championships."

24:58.040 --> 24:58.957
And I'm like,

24:59.041 --> 25:02.044
"You're right.
